── 🔴 CRITICAL (2) ──

  [MG003] Full escalation chain detected (single-server)
  Category: compositional | Confidence: medium
  The MCP configuration contains a complete source → egress → sink escalation chain across single-server tools. Sources: [vulnerable-server/run_query, vulnerable-server/read_file, vulnerable-server/http_fetch]. Egress: [vulnerable-server/http_fetch]. Sinks: [vulnerable-server/run_query, vulnerable-server/execute_command, vulnerable-server/write_file]. This combination allows data to be read, exfiltrated over the network, and used for arbitrary writes or command execution.
  Exploit: An attacker chains: (1) use source tool(s) [vulnerable-server/run_query, vulnerable-server/read_file, vulnerable-server/http_fetch] to access sensitive data, (2) use egress tool(s) [vulnerable-server/http_fetch] to exfiltrate data to an external server, (3) use sink tool(s) [vulnerable-server/run_query, vulnerable-server/execute_command, vulnerable-server/write_file] to write, execute, or deploy malicious payloads — achieving full data exfiltration and code execution.
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[run_query] — Source tool 'run_query' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: source:query, sink:execute)
    Raw: tool=run_query, server=vulnerable-server, role=source, matched_keywords=[source:query, sink:execute]
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[read_file] — Source tool 'read_file' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: source:read)
    Raw: tool=read_file, server=vulnerable-server, role=source, matched_keywords=[source:read]
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[http_fetch] — Source tool 'http_fetch' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: source:fetch, egress:http)
    Raw: tool=http_fetch, server=vulnerable-server, role=source, matched_keywords=[source:fetch, egress:http]
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[http_fetch] — Egress tool 'http_fetch' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: source:fetch, egress:http)
    Raw: tool=http_fetch, server=vulnerable-server, role=egress, matched_keywords=[source:fetch, egress:http]
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[run_query] — Sink tool 'run_query' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: source:query, sink:execute)
    Raw: tool=run_query, server=vulnerable-server, role=sink, matched_keywords=[source:query, sink:execute]
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[execute_command] — Sink tool 'execute_command' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: sink:execute)
    Raw: tool=execute_command, server=vulnerable-server, role=sink, matched_keywords=[sink:execute]
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[write_file] — Sink tool 'write_file' on server 'vulnerable-server' (signals: sink:write)
    Raw: tool=write_file, server=vulnerable-server, role=sink, matched_keywords=[sink:write]
  Remediation: Break the single-server escalation chain: restrict egress tools to approved destinations, scope source tools to non-sensitive data, remove unnecessary exec/write sinks, add authorization gates between tools, or split into separate configs with distinct trust domains.
  CWE: CWE-269, CWE-284 | OWASP: A01:2021 | MCP: MCP02:2025, MCP03:2025

  [MG004] Unconfined filesystem access in tool 'write_file' via parameter 'path'
  Category: static | Confidence: high
  Tool 'write_file' (server 'vulnerable-server') accepts an unconstrained path parameter 'path' for filesystem operations. No allowedDirectories, basePath, pattern, or enum constraints are defined, allowing arbitrary filesystem access including writes.
  Exploit: An attacker provides a path like '../../etc/passwd' or '/etc/shadow' to parameter 'path' in tool 'write_file', traversing outside any intended directory scope to overwrite or delete sensitive files.
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[write_file] > parameters[path] — Unconstrained path parameter 'path' in filesystem tool with no directory scoping
    Raw: { "name": "path", "type": "string", "constraints": {} }
  Remediation: Add path constraints to parameter 'path': define 'allowedDirectories' or 'basePath' to confine access to specific directories. Add a 'pattern' constraint to reject path traversal sequences. Consider using a chroot or sandbox for filesystem tools.
  CWE: CWE-22, CWE-73 | OWASP: A01:2021 | MCP: MCP05:2025, MCP10:2025

── 🟠 HIGH (9) ──

  [MG001] Unbounded string 'command' flows to dangerous sink in tool 'execute_command'
  Category: static | Confidence: high
  Parameter 'command' in tool 'execute_command' (server 'vulnerable-server') is an unconstrained string that flows to dangerous operation(s): exec, execute, run, shell, command. No enum, pattern, maxLength, or format constraints are defined.
  Exploit: An attacker controlling the 'command' parameter can inject malicious content targeting the exec, execute, run, shell, command sink(s). For example, if this is a SQL query parameter, the attacker could execute 'DROP TABLE users; --' or exfiltrate data via UNION-based injection.
  Evidence: fixtures/vulnerable.tools.json > servers[vulnerable-server] > tools[execute_command] > parameters[command] — Unconstrained string parameter 'command' with type 'string' and no validation constraints, in tool with dangerous sink indicators: exec, execute, run, shell, command
    Raw: { "name": "command", "type": "string", "constraints": {} }
  Remediation: Add input constraints to parameter 'command': use an enum for known values, a regex pattern for structured input, maxLength to limit size, or a format specifier. Consider parameterized queries for SQL sinks and allowlists for command execution.
  CWE: CWE-77, CWE-89, CWE-78 | OWASP: A03:2021 | MCP: MCP05:2025, MCP06:2025

